subSection.paragraph:
Prenylated flavonoids are a class of flavonoids that combine the backbone of 2-phenylchromen-4-one (2-phenyl-1-benzopyran-4-one) and a lipophilic prenyl side-chain. The prenyl side-chain generally refers to alkyl-substituent groups, such as prenyl, geranyl and farnesyl groups as well as the variations of these alkyl groups depend on their hydroxylation, cyclization and oxidation (
Fig. 1
) (
Mukne et al., 2011
). Besides, prenylation occurs on the skeletons of flavone, dihydroflavone, isoflavone, flavane and chalcone, which result in diverse sub-classes of prenylated flavonoids. (
Fig. 1
) (Smejkal et al., 2014; 
Liu et al., 2019
). These two reasons lead to many structural possibilities of prenylated flavonoids. According to a conservative estimate, more than 1000 prenylated polyphenols have been isolated and identified from the plant kingdom, most of which are xanthones, a unique scaffold with a 9 
H
-xanthen-9-one core structure, and more than 363 xanthones have been isolated and identified from 
Gentianaceae
and 
Hypericaceae
, which has been reported previously (
Yazaki et al., 2009
; 
Feng et al., 2020
; 
Klein-Júnior et al., 2019
; 
Masters et al., 2012
; 
Shagufta et al., 2016
; Vieiral et al., 2005). Thus, this review mainly focused on the core frameworks of prenylated flavonoids including flavone, dihydroflavone, isoflavone, flavane and chalcone. In addition, due to the promising and diverse bioactivities in multitarget tissues, the researches on prenylated flavonoids have become a hot spot, and many medicinal chemists have synthesized semi- and purely synthetic prenylated flavonoids derivatives with different functional groups at different positions of their basic skeleton.

Prenylated flavonoids play an important role in defensive strategy and are considered as the products of inducible metabolites (
Ibrahim et al., 2005
). In the plants, prenylated flavonoids biosynthesis starts from L-phenylalanine or L-tyrosine, and is catalyzed by five enzymes, including phenylalanine ammonia lyase (PAL), tyrosine ammonia lyase (TAL), cinnamate 4-hydroxylase (C4H), cytochrome P450 reductas (CPR) and 4-coumarate-CoA ligase (4CL), so coumaroyl-CoA is produced by mass conversion (
Levisson et al., 2019
). Subsequently, one molecule of coumaroyl-CoA and three molecules of malonyl-CoA yield naringenin chalcone which is catalyzed by enzyme chalcone synthase (CHS). The naringenin chalcone is consequently isomerized by enzyme chalcone flavanone isomerase (CHI) to obtain the basic skeleton of flavonoids. Finally, isoflavone is synthesized catalyzed by 2-hydroxyisoflavanone synthase (IFS) and 2-hydroxyisoflavanone dehydratase (HID) (
Singh et al., 2014
; 
Shen et al., 2012
). At the same time, a lipophilic prenyl side-chain is produced through mevalonic acid (MVA) pathway or methylerythritol phosphate (MEP) pathway (
Li et al., 2012
; 
Wen et al., 2021
). As shown in 
Fig. 2
, the classical MVA pathway starting from acetyl-CoA. Three molecules of acetyl-CoA are converted to isopentenyl pyrophosphate (IPP) and its isomer dimethylallyl diphosphate (DMAPP) through the actions of ERG10, 13 and tHMG1, which are the main prenyl donors in the plants. In addition, the classical MEP pathway begins with the condensation of pyruvate and glyceraldehyde phosphate to produce 1-deoxy-D-xylulose-5-phosphate (DXP), further to generate 2- 
C
-methyl-D-erythritol-4-phosphate (MEP), CDP-methyl-D-erythritol (CDP-ME), CDP-methyl-D-erythritol-2-phosphate (CDP-MEP), 2-methyl-Derythritol-2,4-diphosphate (MEcDP), 1-hydroxy-2-methyl-2-butenyl-4-diphosphate (HMBDP), IPP and DMAPP (
Wen et al., 2021
). Which through the actions of seven enzymes such as DXP synthase (DXS), DXP reductoisomerase (DXR), CDP-methyl-D-erythritol synthase (MCT), CDP-methyl-D-erythritol kinase (CMK), 2- 
C
-methyl-D-erythritol-2, 4-diphosphate (MDS), 1-hydroxy-2-methyl-2-butenyl-4-diphosphate (HDS) and 1-hydroxy-2-methyl-2-butenyl-4-diphosphate reductase (HDR). Then, DMAPP and its isomer IPP are converted to longer prenyl donors, such as geranyl diphosphate (GPP) and farnesyl diphosphate (FPP) by the regulation of endogenous FPP synthase (ERG20) (
Sasaki et al., 2008
). Furthermore, the condensation of flavonoids and prenyl donors can produce diverse of prenylated flavonoids, which is performed by the enzyme of flavonoid prenyltransferase (SfFPT) such as SfN8DT-1, SfG6DT, SfiLDT, G4DT and LaPT1 (
Chen et al., 2013
; 
Akashi et al., 2009
; 
Nicolaou et al., 2007
; 
Khupse et al., 2007
; 
Shen et al., 2012
). It is a crucial step in the biosynthesis of prenylated flavonoids in plants (
Fig. 2
).

The former reviews summarized only the cytotoxic potential of Cprenylated flavonoids in 2013 and 2019, or only the antioxidant activity of prenyl flavonoids in 2020 (
Smejkal et al., 2013
; 
Lenka et al., 2019
; 
Santos et al., 2020
). In this review, we mainly described the pharmacological activities including cytotoxicity, anti-inflammatory, anti-- Alzheimer, anti-microbial, anti-oxidant, anti-diabetic, estrogenic vasorelaxant and enzyme inhibitory activities of prenylated flavonoids. We identified a systematic literature search with a limitation of being published from 2000 to 2021. The search terms were “prenylated flavonoids,” “prenyl flavonoids,” “prenylation flavonoids” and the related activity combinations of these keywords through several search engines including SciFinder, Web of Science, Google Scholar and Bing Scholar. According to the articles extracted from these databases, we found that most of the studies focused on in vitro studies, and only a few studies investigated on animal models, with rarely any clinical studies.

Cancer in various forms is one of the deadliest health hazards, which has always been one of the major challenges facing humanity. It involves the cell proliferation, differentiation, angiogenesis, and apoptosis of the normal cells which leads to tumor conditions. In order to reduce the human mortality or suppress the further development of cancer, chemoprevention and chemotherapy are a common treatment method. Although various anticancer agents have been used to treat different kinds of cancers through acting on different mechanisms, these agents are not only cytotoxicity towards tumor cells but also normal cells due to their lack of selectivity. Therefore, the acquisition of anti-tumor drugs from natural products has attracted more and more attention from medicinal chemists. Prenylated flavonoids are a large group of naturally occurring flavonoids characterized by the presence of a prenylated side-chain on the flavonoid skeleton. The prenyl side-chain could enhance the binding affinity of flavonoids toward P-glycoprotein, which results in remarkable improvement of biological activity of the flavonoids (
Nguyen et al., 2014
). In recent research, prenylated flavonoids have been recognized as compounds with potential cytotoxicity against various cancer cells.

To date, around 44 prenylated flavonoids (
123–166
) have been reported from the plants of 

Daphne giraldii
(Thymelaeaceae)

by our researcher group in 2016–2019 for the first time (
Li et al., 2016
; 
Sun et al., 2016a
, b; 
Sun et al., 2016a
; 
Sun et al., 2018
; 
Sun et al., 2017
; 
Yao et al., 2018
). Interestingly, most of the isolates were the enantiomers of prenylated flavans, and had a selective cytotoxicity against hepatic carcinoma cell lines through the mechanism of inducing apoptosis and ROS accumulation in Hep3B cells. Among these compounds, daphnegiranol D1 and D2 (
143
and 
144
) are the pair of prenylated flavan enantiomers, which share the 7-hydroxyflavan skeleton with a 2-hydroxy-3,3-dimethyldihydropyran ring, and an additional prenyl group on the B ring at position C-3’. MTT assays showed that daphnegiranol D1 and D2 had a selectively cytotoxic effect against Hep3B cells with the IC 
50
value of 4.87 and 3.35 μM, respectively, which showed more potent than the positive control sorafenib (IC 
50
= 6.59 μM). Additionally, 22 natural prenylated flavonoids (
167–196
) (
Fig. 3
) (
Table 1
) were evaluated their cytotoxicity against several human cell lines in vitro by the MTT method (
Li et al., 2014b
; 
Liu et al., 2018
; 
Long et al., 2021
; 
Fu et al., 2011
; 
Ogungbe et al., 2011
; 
Su et al., 2012
; 
Yang et al., 2014a
, b; 
Ye et al., 2021
). The result indicated that prenylated isoflavones (
174–181
) exhibited the significant anti-proliferative effects against five human cancer cell lines such as HL-60, SMMC-7721, A-549, MCF-7 and SW480 with IC 
50
values ranging from 0.16 to 12.68 μM.

Over the past decades, numerous studies were focused on the modification of substitutions in the prenylated flavonoid scaffold to get more potent compounds. In 2011, a series of prenyl flavonoid derivatives (
197–207
) (
Fig. 4
])was designed and synthesized, and their cytotoxic activity against five human cancer cell lines including K562, PC-3, MCF-7, A549 and HO8910 was measured using the MTT assay (
Ou et al., 2011
). From the results of screening activities (
Table 2
), compound 
198
containing a long prenyl side chain (C 
7
H 
13
), which exhibited the most potent cytotoxic activity with IC 
50
values of 2.76–6.98 μM. Similarly, two series of different prenyl flavonoid derivatives (
208–230
) have been synthesized by Sunil Kumar et al. (
Fig. 5
), and the MTT method was used to evaluated their anti-proliferative activity against three human tumor cell lines including Mia PaCa-2, PC-3 and HL-60 (
Table 3
) (
Kumar et al., 2015
). Unfortunately, the outcome showed that most of the derivatives did not exhibit better anti-proliferative activities than the parent compound 4 
′
-methoxy licoflavanone (
208
).

Inflammation is an adaptive mechanism used by the human immune system in response to microbial invasion or harmful stimulus (
Medzhitov et al., 2008
). In general, inflammation is a complex process in human body involving a number of inflammatory mediators such as reactive oxygen species (ROS), interleukin (IL)-1β, tumor necrosis factor-α (TNF-α), IL-6, nitric oxide (NO), and NF-kB, etc. (
Laskin et al., 2011
). In addition, some signaling proteins such as extracellular signal-related kinase (ERK)-1/2, p38 mitogen-activated protein kinase (MAPK), c-Jun NH 
2
-terminal kinase (JNK), and phosphoinositide 3-kinase (PI3K)/Akt and NF-κB also control the inflammation response (
Zhang et al., 2001
). Up to now, in spite of many marketed drugs that treat inflammation through a variety of different mechanisms, it is still not feasible to successfully treat inflammatory disorders. Therefore, there is a need for developing new agents with action mechanisms different from the conventional anti-inflammatory drugs. Interestingly, prenylated flavonoids and its derivatives with anti-inflammatory activities have been reported continuously (Han´akova´et al., 2015).

