Nitric oxide (NO) is a short-lived radical gas and cellular signaling molecule generated from 
L
-arginine catalyzed by nitric oxide synthase (NOS) (
Xie et al., 1994
). Inducible NOS will produce high levels of NO, which plays an important role in regulating immunomodulatory and inflammatory responses (
Salerno et al., 2002
; 
Passante et al., 2009
). However, excessive production of NO can lead to inflammatory diseases in the immune system. Thus, inhibiting the production of NO can provide a new way to find the potential anti-inflammatory drugs.

In addition, β- hexosaminidase is a chemical mediator and considered to be the parameters of mast cell degranulation (
Passante et al., 2009
). Mast cell degranulation will lead to the acute response, such as increased vascular permeability, inflammation, vasodilation and so on (
Lee et al., 2015
). Thus, inhibiting the release of β- hexosaminidase is also a rational way to treat inflammation. A series of prenylated flavonoids derivatives (
359–368
) (
Fig. 9
) (
Table 5
) was isolated from the fruit of 

Cudrania tricuspidata

and evaluated for their inhibitory effects of β- hexosaminidase (
Lee et al., 2015
). However, expect for compound 
363
, which could inhibit the release of β- hexosaminidase in FcεRI-mediated mast cells with an IC 
50
value of 20.4 μM, and the rest of prenylated flavonoid derivatives had no apparent inhibitory activity.

Alzheimer’ s disease (AD) is an age-related progressive neurodegenerative disease, characterized by progressive and irreversible cognitive deterioration, memory loss and behavioral disturbances (
Shal et al., 2018
). It is an alarming fact that three-quarters of the world’ s population older than 60 years of age are expected to suffer from AD by 2025 according to the World Health Organization (
Kwon et al., 2016
). To date, no consensus has been reached on the cause of AD. However, with the increasing research on AD, several hypotheses have been proposed based upon the various pathophysiological factors observed, including amyloid beta (Aβ) peptide deposits, deficits of acetylcholine (ACh), tau protein aggregation, dyshomeostasis of biometals, and oxidative stress (
Wang et al., 2014
). Prenylated flavonoids, an important class of small molecule natural polyphenolic phytochemicals, have been reported to be effective in the treatment of AD.

The cholinesterases (ChEs) serve as the key enzymes which are highly implicated in the pathogenesis of AD, and the ChEs inhibitors might be more effective for the prevention and treatment of AD. During the study of screening for the anti-AD activity of the traditional medicine 

Morus alba
(Moraceae)

, kuwanon G (
34
) (
Fig. 3
) was obtained from the plant and exhibited good ChEs enzyme inhibitory activity with IC 
50
values of 20.4–37.07 μM (
Table 6
) (
Kuk et al., 2017
). In addition, the molecular docking results coincided with the kinetic analysis in vitro, which revealed that compound 
370
has high binding affinity with the targets of AChE and BACE1, and therefore it is an effective AChE and BACE1 inhibitors. In addition, the studies of flavonoids as lead compounds for the treatment of AD reported the activities of a series of prenylated flavonoids (
33
, 
79
, 
370–383
) (
Figs. 3
, 

12

) (
Table 6
) (
Anand et al., 2013
; 
Kim et al., 2011
; 
Nie et al., 2009
; 
Zeng et al., 2010
). In this studies, prenylated flavonoid was reported as various enzyme targets including cholinesterase (AChE and BChE), beta secretase, glycogen synthase kinase-3β and NADPH, which play an important role in the pathogenesis of AD, respectively. Moreover, 6-hydroxydopamine (6-OHDA) and 1-methyl-4-phenylpyridinium ion (MPP 
+
) generate excessive reactive oxygen species and elicit dopaminergic neuronal cell death, which also contributes to the progress of AD (
Kwon et al., 2014
; 
Hiep et al., 2014
). Several prenylated flavonoids (
384–387
) (
Fig. 12
) (
Table 6
) and other natural compounds were isolated from the root bark of 

Cudrania tricuspidate

and their neuroprotective effects against 6-OHDA and MPP 
+
were evaluated (
Kwon et al., 2016
). However, the result indicated that these prenylated flavonoids (EC 
50
>
50 μM) are less active than other isolates.

The increasing development of bacterial resistance to antibiotics is a major difficulty to the successful treatment of infectious diseases caused by bacteria ( Brown et al., 2016 ). Due to the characteristic of rapid spread, the bacteria can be easily and quickly carried from one continent to another, which poses huge threats to public health ( Brown et al., 2016 ). There is an urgent need for developing novel antimicrobial agents without cross resistance to successful treatment of the disease caused by bacteria . In this context, many researcher groups have concentrated their efforts on developing effective antimicrobial agents without cross resistance. Natural products have particularly been a rich source of anti-infective agents, so many semisynthetic or synthetic compounds with remarkable anti-infective activities have been designed and synthesized by lead optimization of natural scaffolds (
Cushnie et al ., 2005
). Prenylated flavonoids have been reported for protective role against microbial invasion in the plants. Due to this protective role, this class of natural products is becoming the subject of anti-infective research.

Malaria is the major parasitic infection and remains one of the most prevalent and mortal diseases in the world, principally in Sub Saharan Africa (
Zhang et al., 2001
). In view of resistance even to newly introduced drugs, continued efforts to develop new antimalarial drugs are needed (
Achan et al., 2018
). The prenylated flavonoid scaffold can be considered as a promising skeleton for further exploiting new effective anti-parasite drugs (
Botta et al., 2009
).

The high levels of free radicals in living systems are harmful to human health, which mainly caused cell death, tissue damage and various diseases such as neurological disease, inflammation, cancer, arteriosclerosis and cardiovascular disease through oxidizing the biomolecules (
Ilhami, 2008
). The antioxidants mainly act through scavenging radicals, mostly hydroxyl radicals, and thereby inhibiting the chain of oxidative events that leads to damage of proteins and lipid membranes. In addition, by inhibiting superoxide anion and reactive oxygen species (ROS) production, degrading hydrogen peroxide and chelating or reducing metal ions, the antioxidants play an essential role in the human health (
Wen et al., 2020
). Several methods have been frequently used to estimate antioxidant capacity in free radical biology such as 1,1-diphenyl-2-picrylhydrazyl (DPPH) radical assays, 2,2-azino-- bis-3-ethylbenzthiazoline-6-sulphonic acid (ABTS 
•+
) scavenging assays, and ferric reducing antioxidant power (FRAP) assays. It was reported that prenylated flavonoids have well known antioxidant activity via several pathways.

Diabetes is a kind of metabolic disease affecting more and more people all over the world. Various enzymes like a-glucosidase, protein kinase C (PKC), PPAR-γ (peroxisome proliferator activated receptor-γ) are linked directly or indirectly with diabetes. The disease can be controlled by various anti-diabetic agents through various acting mechanisms, such as increase in insulin secretion from pancreatic β- cells (sulphonylureas), enhancement of insulin action (PPAR-γ agonists) and reduction of hepatic glucose production (α- glucosidase inhibitors) (
Fuhlendorff et al., 1998
; 
Daniele, 2008
; 
Dewi et al., 2014
). Interestingly, prenylated flavonoids have been reported for the treatment of diabetes through inhibiting α- glucosidase or activating PPAR-γ.

Estrogens have been shown to exert a variety of beneficial effects on the human health, such as providing protection against menopausal symptoms, osteoporosis, cardiovascular disease, and some potentially neurodegenerative diseases. Moreover, estrogens are also one of the most important risk factors for breast cancer (
Galluzzo et al., 2006
). As estrogen-like compounds play a crucial role in preventing and treating estrogen-mediated diseases, searching for estrogen-like compounds with remarkable activities has been an attractive area for science community (
Botta et al., 2005
). Phytoestrogens are the non-steroidal plant-derived compounds that functionally mimic mammalian estrogens. Thus, they are also considered to play an important role in preventing menopausal symptoms, osteoporosis, cancer and heart disease (
Vitale et al., 2013
).

