Cardiovascular disease has gradually become the highest incidence and more people die from the disease than from any other cause in the world annually, according to the World Health Organization report. Existing researchers have found that one of the main causes for cardiovascular diseases is the involvement of vascular tissues through losing their capacity to relax. Therefore, in order to effectively treat cardiovascular disease, many research groups have paid much attention to the vascular studies (
Jackman et al., 2007
; 
Koenig et al., 2007
; 
Motahare et al., 2019
).

Tyrosinase plays an essential role for melanin synthesis in mammals, and its overproduction will result in skin hyperpigmentations, such as melasma, chloasma and age spots (
Tachibana et al., 2003
). In addition, compared with normal cells, the expression level of tyrosinase in tumor cells was significantly up-regulated and its activity also increased (
Sang et al., 2015
; 
Qiang et al., 2014
). Thus, tyrosinase inhibitors have attracted considerable attention from drug researchers. Interestingly, many reports have proved that prenylated flavonoids exhibited remarkable tyrosinase inhibitory activity through different mechanisms of action (
Nguyen et al., 2014
; 
Sang et al., 2015
; 
Qiang et al., 2014
).

Aromatase is a key enzyme in estrogen biosynthesis, and inhibition of aromatas is being explored as a target germane to the prevention or treatment of prostate and breast cancers (Kumaraswamy et al., 1998; 
Cassidy et al., 2010
). A large number of synthetic compounds and various classes of natural products have been evaluated for their inhibitory potential towards aromatase. Four prenylated flavonoids derivatives (
507–510
) (
Fig. 20
) were obtained from 

Broussonetia papyrifera
(Moraceae)

through the bioassay-guided separation method, and evaluated their aromatase inhibitory activity in vitro assay (
Table 12
) (
Lee et al., 2001
). The result indicated that compounds 
509
and 
510
showed the most potent aromatase inhibitory activity with IC 
50
values of 0.5 μM and 0.1 μM, respectively. In addition, an interesting study by Manika Awasthi et al. used comparative molecular field analysis (CoMFA) and molecular dynamics (MD) simulation analysis for virtual screening of flavonoids as inhibitors of aromatase. From the result, several prenylated flavonoids (
511–515
) (
Fig. 20
) (
Table 12
) exhibited potent aromatase inhibitory activity with IC 
50
values in the range of 0.1–3.4 μM, which provided a foundation for developing prenylated flavonoids into effective anti-aromatase drugs (
Awasthi et al., 2015
).

Though prenylated flavonoids have attractive pharmacological properties, and their occurrence in plant extracts is complicated by the relatively complex mixtures, which means their mass isolation from the plants is not economically attractive (
Botta et al., 2005
). Several synthetic methods have been developed and modified to get products of high yield, purity and of the desired quality. As the backbone of prenylated flavonoids consist of the rings of C6–C3–C6, and they are referred to as A, C, and B rings, respectively. Thus, the prenyl side-chain can be substituted on different rings via different synthesis methods. Herein, we have focused predominantly on reviewing the development of various strategies toward the total synthesis of prenylated flavonoids.

Emerging evidence has shown that the position, number and length of prenyl group on the B-ring also have a marked influence on bioactivities of prenylated flavonoids, and methods for the synthesis prenyl side-chain on the B ring are being investigated by numerous researches (
Motahare et al., 2019
; 
Barron et al., 2020
). Jinhui Yang and her research group have been working on synthesis of the prenylated flavonoids for many years. According to their study, the prenyl side-chain on the B ring can be synthesized by the delocalization of phenoxide anion within the aromatic ring and Claisen-Schmidt condensation (
Fig. 26
) (
Yang et al., 2013a
, 
2013b
; 
Zuo et al., 2012
). The key step was the introduction of the prenyl group to hydroxybenzaldehyde, which proceeded into an unsatisfactory yield. But many medicinal chemists have tried other methods for the prenylation on the phenyl group without much success (
Moriarty et al., 2005
).
